Topic: File Handling in Python


1ï¸âƒ£ Why File Handling?

Until now, data disappears after program ends.
File handling lets you:

Store data permanently

Read saved data

Build real applications

2ï¸âƒ£ Opening a File

Syntax:

file = open("filename.txt", "mode")

Modes:

"r" â†’ read

"w" â†’ write (overwrites file)

"a" â†’ append

"x" â†’ create file

3ï¸âƒ£ Write to File
file = open("demo.txt", "w")
file.write("Hello Akshay\n")
file.write("Python is powerful")
file.close()


ğŸ‘‰ This creates demo.txt.

4ï¸âƒ£ Read from File
file = open("demo.txt", "r")
content = file.read()
print(content)
file.close()

5ï¸âƒ£ Append to File
file = open("demo.txt", "a")
file.write("\nNew line added")
file.close()

6ï¸âƒ£ Best Practice (Important ğŸ”¥)

Use with (auto closes file)

with open("demo.txt", "r") as file:
    print(file.read())


No need for close().

7ï¸âƒ£ Read Line by Line
with open("demo.txt", "r") as file:
    for line in file:
        print(line)

ğŸ§  Memory Trick

w â†’ wipe & write

a â†’ add

r â†’ read

with â†’ safe method
